	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The very simplest way to try how accurate sound is is to start a new game of Final Fantasy VI, and when the gameplay begins listen how the wind sounds, and then try again with a real SNES (since FF6 wind is almost identical to CT wind, only with echo).
<br />
<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Which Super NES games are the pickiest about SPC/DSP behavior?</div>
<br />Games where sound effects samples are hard to emulate proprely (SFX samples rely on clamping sample decoder in noise):
<br />- Chrono Trigger
<br />- Final Fantasy IV
<br />- Final Fantasy V
<br />- Final Fantasy VI
<br />- Romancing Saga
<br />- Romancing Saga II
<br />- Romancing Saga III
<br />- Live A Live
<br />- Secret of Mana
<br />- Seiken Densetsu III
<br />- Rudra no Hihou
<br />- Bahamut Lagoon
<br />- Megaman VII
<br />- Megaman X
<br />- Megaman X2
<br />- Megaman X3
<br />- Breath of Fire
<br />- Castlevania : Dracula X
<br />- Zelda III - A link to the past
<br />- ... most probably a ton of others ...
<br />
<br />Games where music samles are hard to emulate proprely (samples can be emulated as noise while they aren't supposed to be) :
<br />- Dragon Quest III (pizz strings)
<br />- Dragon Quest VI (pizz strings, identical to above)
<br />- Tactics Ogre (brass instruments)
<br />- ... most probably several others ...

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


